# Cloudflare Pages redirects file.
# Format: <source>  <destination>  <status>
# Status codes: 301 (permanent), 302 (temporary), 200 (rewrite/proxy)
#
# Populate from reference/seo-map.csv before launch.
# WordPress migrations should map every indexed URL to its new home (301).
#
# Examples:
# /about-us/        /about/           301
# /old-blog-slug/   /blog/new-slug/   301
#
# Preserve WordPress feed URL for aggregators / email tools / directories:
/feed/            /rss.xml          301
#
# Preserve legacy sitemap path. @astrojs/sitemap outputs `sitemap-index.xml`,
# but WP exposed `sitemap.xml`. Crawlers expecting the WP path get a 404
# unless we redirect:
/sitemap.xml      /sitemap-index.xml    301
#
# IMPORTANT: `_redirects` strips query parameters during matching + forwarding.
# For sites with heavy UTM / gclid / ad-tracking traffic, query-bearing URLs
# (e.g. `/old-page/?utm_source=email`) will redirect to the new path but DROP
# the query string — destroying attribution. For those cases use Cloudflare
# Transform Rules or Bulk Redirects (account-level) which preserve params.
# Docs: https://developers.cloudflare.com/rules/transform/url-rewrite/
#
# WP /wp-content/uploads/ assets accumulate backlinks too — map them, not just
# HTML pages. Keeping original filenames preserves the backlink graph:
# /wp-content/uploads/2023/*.jpg  /images/legacy/2023/:splat.jpg  301
# /wp-content/uploads/2024/*.pdf  /documents/:splat.pdf            301
# /wp-content/uploads/*           /images/legacy/:splat            301
#
# Cloudflare Pages limits: 2,100 lines. For larger maps, use Bulk Redirects
# at the Cloudflare account level instead.
# Docs: https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/redirects/

